[start section id="20112"]

#1 Recently-diagnosed invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the middescending colon
Mrs. Walters has essentially come to Colonel Florence A Blanchfield Army Hospital for surgical management of this.  In light of her CT-scan from the 17th of June 2010 demonstrating an ill-defined low-density area seen centrally in the liver, we are arranging an MRI of the liver to evaluate for any possible metastatic spread.  We will schedule Mrs. Walters to be seen by a colorectal surgeon for further management of this.  Her main concern is that she does not wish to have a colostomy, which she had back in the 1970s, and this will be discussed further with the surgeons.  Her pathology slides from the outside hospital have been given to Colonel Florence A Blanchfield Army Hospital this morning.
#2 Preoperative assessment and medical clearance
Mrs. Walters had an ECG performed on the 15th of June 2010 that demonstrated normal sinus rhythm with no significant abnormality seen.  The chest x-ray from the 15th of June 2010 demonstrated underinflated lungs with slight scarring or atelectasis in the bases with the chest appearance otherwise negative.  Her lab results frmo the 16th of June 2010 demonstrated a microcytic anemia with a hemoglobin of 11.6 with a low platelet count of 67,000.  Her electrolytes were within normal limits.  Her renal function was normal and she is ok for surgery from a medical standpoint, but her platelet count should be monitored carefully. In regards to her diabetes, this is poorly-controlled with an HbA1c of 11.6 on the 16th of June 2010.  After discussion with Dr. Mendiola, it was felt that once she is admitted to the hospital, then the diabetes consulting service should follow her for more management of her diabetes perioperatively.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

